      'How long does stucco last? It is one of the most common questions San Antonio homeowners ask — whether they are considering a new stucco installation, evaluating a home to purchase, or trying to figure out how much life is left in their existing exterior. The short answer is 50 to 80 years for a properly installed three-coat cement stucco system. The real answer depends on installation quality, climate exposure, and maintenance.',
      '## Stucco Lifespan by System Type',
      'Traditional three-coat cement stucco is the gold standard for longevity. When installed correctly over proper lath and moisture barriers, a three-coat system in San Antonio can last 50 to 80 years before it needs full replacement. Many homes in Alamo Heights, Monte Vista, and the King William District have original stucco from the 1920s and 1930s that is still structurally sound nearly a century later.',
      'One-coat stucco systems, which became popular in production homebuilding during the 1990s and 2000s, have a shorter expected lifespan of 20 to 40 years. The thinner application is more vulnerable to cracking, moisture intrusion, and finish deterioration, especially in the demanding San Antonio climate. Many one-coat homes built 15 to 25 years ago are now reaching the point where significant repairs or replacement are needed.',
      'EIFS (synthetic stucco) lifespan varies widely based on installation quality and maintenance. A well-installed, well-maintained EIFS system can last 30 to 50 years. However, EIFS systems without proper drainage planes — common in 1980s and 1990s installations throughout Stone Oak and other San Antonio neighborhoods — may develop moisture problems within 15 to 20 years that require major remediation.',
      '## What Shortens Stucco Lifespan in San Antonio',
      'Installation quality is the single biggest factor. Stucco that was installed with skipped layers, insufficient curing time between coats, improperly placed expansion joints, or missing moisture barriers will fail decades earlier than a properly installed system. Unfortunately, many production homes in San Antonio were built with cost-saving shortcuts that homeowners do not discover until problems appear.',
      'Climate stress is the second factor. San Antonio subjects stucco to extreme thermal cycling (up to 60-degree daily temperature swings in summer), intense UV radiation that degrades coatings, high humidity that tests moisture barriers, and seasonal soil movement from expansive clay that stresses foundations and walls. All of these accelerate aging compared to stucco in milder climates.',
      'Deferred maintenance is the third factor. Small cracks that go unrepaired become moisture entry points. Failed sealant joints around windows let water behind the wall. Vegetation growing against the surface traps moisture and causes localized deterioration. Each of these issues compounds over time, and what starts as a minor cosmetic problem can evolve into substrate damage that shortens the overall system life significantly.',
      '## How to Maximize Your Stucco Lifespan',
      'Inspect your stucco twice a year — once in spring before the heat arrives, once in fall after storm season. Look for new cracks, staining, sealant gaps, and any areas where the finish looks different. Address cracks and sealant failures promptly; in San Antonio, a small crack in March becomes a moisture problem by August. Keep vegetation at least 12 inches away from stucco surfaces. Clean gently once a year with a garden hose and soft brush. Apply a breathable masonry sealer every three to five years. Budget for a professional re-coat every 15 to 25 years to refresh the UV protection and color.',
      '## When Repair Is Enough vs. When Replacement Is Needed',
      'If your stucco is cracking in isolated areas, has cosmetic staining, or has sealant failures at penetrations, repair is almost always sufficient and far more cost-effective than replacement. If damage is widespread across multiple walls, the substrate behind the stucco is rotted or mold-damaged, or the stucco was originally installed with critical layers missing, replacement is the right call.',
